31:25.250 --> 31:28.935
question. How would you describe or profile a 
typical veterinarian or a student or someone that

31:28.975 --> 31:39.448
you think should be in that kind of business? Do you 
have an image of a veterinarian?

31:44.595 --> 31:47.018
I have an image of what a veterinarian ought to be. 
What is that? Yes. And my image may be false.

31:57.362 --> 32:03.548
Number one, he's got to be accurate. Accuracy of 
the technology, the skill, the art. And you know

32:11.134 --> 32:15.718
we've lost a great part of the art.

32:16.419 --> 32:17.019
What do you mean by that? Parenthetically, here 
then. Dr. A. A. Leonard, who used to be the head of

32:22.566 --> 32:33.782
the clinics,

32:22.566 --> 32:33.782
was an artist.

32:33.802 --> 32:40.491
He could go out there and look at an animal and say, 
he didn't have to test. I don't mean he didn't have

32:40.511 --> 32:46.039
to test, but often he didn't have to run tests. He 
had the visual capability of perceiving what that

32:50.238 --> 32:51.740
was. And that's an art. That's not a skill. That's 
an art. You work on that. Today we have tests,

32:59.691 --> 33:05.519
tests, tests, tests, tests, you see. And there's 
nothing wrong with tests. But we are losing the art

33:07.702 --> 33:13.950
of the practice of that. I don't want to put words in 
your mouth. Getting into more skills. So it's more

33:16.876 --> 33:19.720
technology-oriented than... Absolutely. Well, 
we didn't have the technology. So we had to do the

33:23.645 --> 33:26.009
art. And, you know, when I say art and skills, I 
guess art is a skill, too. No, I know what you mean.

33:37.825 --> 33:43.313
The intuition to say, that's that. Well, I know 
that, for instance, way back there in the 1930s,

33:44.052 --> 34:12.083
Byrne Scott came to our place, and Dad had called

33:44.052 --> 34:12.083
him, and he came, and Dad had a cow in the corral, and 
she wasn't doing anything good either. Dad

34:12.103 --> 34:12.844
obviously knew she was ill. Dr. Berne Scott looked 
over the fence and said, yeah. He says, she has

34:15.891 --> 34:19.475
hardware disease. I said, what's hardware 
disease? He says, it's traumatic pericarditis. I

34:29.768 --> 34:31.210
said, what? He said, no. Cleared that right out.

34:36.837 --> 34:38.960
Well, I sure know she did. There were certain signs 
and symptoms that that animal displayed that he

34:40.642 --> 34:52.897
had seen so many times that he knew what that was. He 
didn't have to go any further. Now, that is skill,

34:54.960 --> 34:57.583
but it's also art. And we have lost a lot of that. You 
know, the old cow, he's tipped. She's got metal in

35:06.318 --> 35:10.743
her, pericardium in her heart. She swallows a nail 
or a wire or something. It goes into the stomach,

35:14.927 --> 35:16.569
into the rumen. The rumen sits just behind the 
diaphragm, and the heart's over on this side

35:17.069 --> 35:21.874
beating. And you try to put a hammer on the handle by 
hitting one end. So literally, that's what's

35:27.520 --> 35:29.382
happening. And the little heart's sitting there 
beating. It just draws that thing right through

35:32.225 --> 35:34.047
the... diaphragm and into the pericardium, the 
covering of the heart. And all kinds of organisms

35:38.578 --> 35:45.968
in the room go in there, and she has an 
inflammation, an infection of the pericardium.

35:46.268 --> 35:47.089
Traumatic. It was traumatic pericarditis.

35:57.382 --> 36:03.029
So a veterinarian is someone who is technically 
skilled in the factory. Yeah. At this day and time,

36:04.469 --> 36:08.974
he has to have the technology to compete. You can't 
do it without the techniques and the implements

36:08.994 --> 36:17.044
and the gadgetry that you've developed. But to 
tell you the thing, one of the biggest things today

36:17.064 --> 36:30.780
is non-invasive techniques, sonar and all this, 
so that you can see what's inside without invading

36:31.503 --> 36:33.427
the body of an invasive. And that's a great 
problem. Because any time you invade the body, the

36:36.694 --> 36:47.617
flesh, you cause a potential problem of infection 
and this sort of thing. You can see what's in there

36:47.637 --> 36:50.142
without doing that. You're way ahead of the game. 
So we're getting better and better and better with

36:53.440 --> 37:01.512
the technology, and it's going to get better and 
better, and the skills are going to be less and

36:53.440 --> 37:01.512
less. And when I say skills and arts, they're going 
to continue to subside. And I'm not saying that's

37:06.740 --> 37:10.626
wrong at all. So you've got to have the technology 
this day and time. Used to it had to be the arts and

37:13.290 --> 37:17.236
the skills, and now the technology. Now the second 
thing the guy's got to have is public relations.

37:24.811 --> 37:25.892
He's got to like people. He's got to know people and 
relate to people. We have so many

37:32.061 --> 37:41.553
little girls coming. Girls, women, young women 
come to get their medicine because they fell in

37:41.573 --> 37:51.046
love with a horse. Well, I'm not going to get on with 
that. But you've got to have more than that. Some of

37:54.747 --> 37:58.350
them will say, well, I just love animals. Shoot, 
you wouldn't want a veterinarian if you didn't

37:58.370 --> 38:01.573
love animals. But that's just the beginning of it. 
So that is an innate part of veterinary medicine is

38:04.796 --> 38:08.860
an affection, let's say, for animals. Oh, yeah. 
You have to have compassion for the welfare of the

38:09.700 --> 38:13.544
animal. But on the other hand, we can't overlook 
the needs of the client. You're working for a

38:20.890 --> 38:22.932
client, not for an animal.

38:25.848 --> 38:27.971
And you've got to face those two also. There are 
times when you can't do what you want to do. Well,

38:34.419 --> 38:36.682
for one reason, it's too expensive. And you know 
that you could make that animal better, maybe

38:37.944 --> 38:48.297
heal, if you could do what you really wanted to do. 
But you can't afford to do it because it would cost

38:49.519 --> 38:55.146
more than that animal is worth. you know, we don't 
have that problem. You do it. And insurance covers

38:59.973 --> 39:02.216
it or something. On that same line, I know this is 
the right place to do it because we need to get back

39:02.236 --> 39:17.357
to the profile of a veterinarian, but as I see it 
too, one of the difficulties in promoting or

39:02.236 --> 39:17.357
advancing the practice of veterinary medicine 
has been the problem of cost. So, for example, In

39:19.932 --> 39:25.480
fact, I was raised with the idea that animals are 
basically expendable, that you don't spend money

39:19.932 --> 39:25.480
on them. I never spent a nickel on a pet. They were 
always free, and if they died, tough. You don't do

39:29.826 --> 39:30.847
that. I spend on them. That's an old agrarian 
philosophy, though. That's right, but I spend a

39:33.751 --> 39:36.756
lot of money on my dogs now. Yeah, well, we've got to 
round to the humans. animal barn today, you know.

39:41.940 --> 39:45.804
Yeah, and your high-priced equipment you're 
talking about is expensive stuff. Absolutely. So

39:46.405 --> 39:55.014
has part of the problem of veterinary medicine 
been convincing people that they need to invest in

39:46.405 --> 39:55.014
their animals? I'm not sure if I'm asking that 
question correctly, but that somehow or other, in

39:55.355 --> 40:05.626
other words, you can prove the efficiencies, the 
cost efficiencies of taking care of animals. Is

40:05.726 --> 40:06.747
that part of the of the message that veterinarians 
have had to get across in the Southwest? Well, you

40:11.475 --> 40:16.460
know, you can sort of classify people in two 
categories in that regard. Those who have

40:16.540 --> 40:22.085
compassion for and will go all out for their 
animal. And those who say, well, it's just a dog.

40:26.129 --> 40:27.270
Yeah. And there's a vast difference in that. This 
one over here will pay the price. There's no way.

40:35.578 --> 40:35.738
Yeah. Now, you know, they meld together in here, 
and they're not two extremes, but nevertheless,

40:36.190 --> 40:56.192
you have to know, as a veterinarian, as a private 
clinical practitioner, they have to know that

40:36.190 --> 40:56.192
this individual wants this dog fixed, no matter 
the cost. This one over here, no, he just wants to

40:56.973 --> 41:02.639
know, should have killed him. You know? And you've 
got all that in there. And you've got to weasel that

41:04.902 --> 41:09.688
out of the people of your clients. Your dog can't 
tell you that. And you don't know that, so you've

41:11.972 --> 41:15.436
got to get it from within. And that's where the 
human relationship has to come in, to know what

41:15.456 --> 41:20.904
that client wants done. That's really an 
intriguing and key point. And if you please that

41:25.069 --> 41:29.495
client, you've got a regular client. If you 
displease that client, And going somewhere else.

41:33.670 --> 41:38.377
And that's the way you build your business, is 
people relationship, not animals. Has that

41:38.737 --> 41:39.979
changed over the years? I mean, when you were 
growing up in Erath County, imagine all your

41:39.999 --> 41:47.370
neighbors were farmers, agriculturists. 
Animals were a means of production. They were

41:51.275 --> 41:51.856
pets. There wasn't necessarily a bond with the 
milk cows or with whatever, you know. Oh, Boston

41:58.372 --> 42:00.795
gets pretty close to the family. All right, but 
you're... You know, but as people move to the city,

42:00.935 --> 42:09.687
as they have pets for whatever reasons, there's a 
completely different attitude. My wife's from a

42:09.727 --> 42:10.508
farm. I'm not. And, you know, we run into that all 
the time. Because she's got one set of values about

42:16.856 --> 42:21.862
animals, and I've got a completely different set 
of values. And it's difficult for me to get around

42:21.882 --> 42:23.124
that. Yeah, you know... There are great extremes 
in this animal side. There's the animal rights

42:29.976 --> 42:33.681
activist, militant. I mean, crazy on that side. 
And then there are those who are just like

42:40.531 --> 42:50.504
barbarians to

42:40.531 --> 42:50.504
animals. In here, there's a better mix, I think. We 
need to be as humane as we can be with animals. I

43:00.607 --> 43:02.670
don't think animals have any rights. You talk 
about animal rights. They don't have any rights.

43:07.996 --> 43:21.012
But we as people ought to be,

43:07.996 --> 43:21.012
well, compassionate enough to treat that animal 
without being a barbarian. We need to treat that

43:22.073 --> 43:23.475
animal carefully and correctly. We don't want to 
cause that animal any pain, and we need to be as

43:29.021 --> 43:38.793
humanitarian as we can possibly be as 
veterinarians. Well, everybody should be free,

43:38.814 --> 43:42.719
not just veterinarians. And if you do that,

43:52.666 --> 43:55.769
You satisfy the activists. And some of the others 
over on this other side say, well, that's stupid.

43:59.633 --> 44:03.237
You're just wasting your money. But let me come 
back to it for you. Veterinarians ought to be

44:06.380 --> 44:21.255
standing for humanitarian

44:06.380 --> 44:21.255
care for the animals under their control or their 
owners. being the owners of what? So we need to do

44:25.776 --> 44:39.773
everything that we can to give that animal a 
comfortable bath time.

44:39.793 --> 44:41.976
Now, money comes into the picture. No question 
about that. And as I said, sometimes you can't do

44:43.658 --> 44:48.083
that because the owner won't let you do that. Won't 
pay the bill. Well, if you don't If you go doing that

44:52.218 --> 44:58.066
for people who don't pay the bill, your business is 
going to fall apart. And you've got to work those

44:58.086 --> 45:01.811
together. But humanitarianism is a very 
essential part of the life of a veterinarian. Yes.

45:08.100 --> 45:12.466
If you dislike animals, you ought not be there. And 
that's one of the things that they, in the

45:12.486 --> 45:20.217
admissions committee, will query the person 
about humanitarianism, you know. How do they feel

45:20.618 --> 45:25.444
about these things? On the other hand, the other 
extreme, that the animal has every right, and you

45:25.464 --> 45:42.366
can't use an animal in any form or shape for 
research, you're violating their rights? Well,

45:43.307 --> 45:46.351
that isn't so. My perception is that animals are 
here for a man. and people use the animals, not the

45:52.107 --> 45:59.275
animals using people. But the people should use 
the animal correctly, humanitarily, and then go

45:59.295 --> 46:09.748
on from there.

